{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"123c7349-1957-479f-ac72-1aac7cd11f1b","content":"In your `App.xaml.cs`, override `CreateWindow` and wire up the lifecycle events:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);\n\n    window.Created  += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Created\");\n    window.Activated   += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Activated\");\n    window.Deactivated += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Deactivated\");\n    window.Stopped     += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Stopped\");\n    window.Resumed     += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Resumed\");\n    window.Destroying  += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Destroying\");\n    window.Backgrounding += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Backgrounding\");\n\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\n**Typical order:**\n\n| Transition | Events |\n|---|---|\n| App launch | `Created → Activated` |\n| Sent to background | `Deactivated → Stopped` |\n| Returned to foreground | `Resumed → Activated` |\n| App closed | `Deactivated → Stopped → Destroying` |\n\n> **Note:** `Backgrounding` fires on **iOS/macCatalyst** only (between `Stopped` and the OS suspending the process). Use it to save state.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8ff03239-c1bf-441f-ac14-20ae4903c023","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI Window lifecycle events and how to subscribe to them for logging/debugging. This is a general knowledge question about .NET MAUI, not related to the repository. I can answer directly.","outputTokens":412,"requestId":"B80F:1EC425:14DE58:1B0616:69FFD831"},"id":"36684b5d-45de-4a6b-aeb0-e2f0870da69e","timestamp":"2026-05-10T00:58:33.106Z","parentId":"f571342b-c016-40b3-b965-6bab98ef3226"}
